column9: well, yes and no

column8: RF&P
column9: it was 2 independant parts, an "A" unit (with a cab) and a "b" unit without a cab

column8: RF&P
column9: at the outset, railroads purchased diesels on a 1:1 replacement basis for steam

column8: RF&P
column9: so they would purchase a certain number of units, with a cab each end to replace 1 steam train

column8: RF&P
column9: usually these consists were A-B-A or A-B-B-A

column8: RF&P
column9: this is of course because american trains were (still are) much longer and heavvier than european

column8: RF&P
column9: Eventually, railroads learned that diesel locomotives were more flexible than steam and started to just put as many locos as needed for any given route

column8: RF&P
column9: so they were usually not permanently coupled to anything at all
